<img srcset="https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/VaDEMWBJoEfvA0MeAIZVIvi7WBM=/0x0:1464x1000/320x0/filters:focal(0x0:1464x1000):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/19394329/depp_fear_and_loathing.jpg 320w, https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/-hMAWWMz7H7AhfRVy2Er3mq7bJk=/0x0:1464x1000/520x0/filters:focal(0x0:1464x1000):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/19394329/depp_fear_and_loathing.jpg 520w, https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/Rrh243KQ1Vu_NmbJIyZM_tTvycw=/0x0:1464x1000/720x0/filters:focal(0x0:1464x1000):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/19394329/depp_fear_and_loathing.jpg 720w, https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/4Jb6fc11f0jogDRr2HmIMplWBB0=/0x0:1464x1000/920x0/filters:focal(0x0:1464x1000):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/19394329/depp_fear_and_loathing.jpg 920w, https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/FoRlZuNpL_QFxWWc1KiSzDNyM7c=/0x0:1464x1000/1120x0/filters:focal(0x0:1464x1000):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/19394329/depp_fear_and_loathing.jpg 1120w, https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/GaST6CEPCrKR79CB8sVT6EKmzMs=/0x0:1464x1000/1320x0/filters:focal(0x0:1464x1000):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/19394329/depp_fear_and_loathing.jpg 1320w, https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/ke7a2-jyEYghgxjOiz_KzLPzktM=/0x0:1464x1000/1520x0/filters:focal(0x0:1464x1000):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/19394329/depp_fear_and_loathing.jpg 1520w, https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/5_S5rV9HFXG-fClrl8hzqk7P2D4=/0x0:1464x1000/1720x0/filters:focal(0x0:1464x1000):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/19394329/depp_fear_and_loathing.jpg 1720w, https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/qQQSx_azXMSNXIbEMcHBbyjwTgw=/0x0:1464x1000/1920x0/filters:focal(0x0:1464x1000):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/19394329/depp_fear_and_loathing.jpg 1920w" sizes="(min-width: 1221px) 846px, (min-width: 880px) calc(100vw - 334px), 100vw" alt="" data-upload-width="1464" src="https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/sBEy5lGnwyB5PSRNVTxk8mYwvp8=/0x0:1464x1000/1200x0/filters:focal(0x0:1464x1000):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/19394329/depp_fear_and_loathing.jpg">

</source></picture>

      
    </span>
    
  </span>
  
    <span class="e-image__meta">
      
      
        <cite>Universal Pictures</cite>
      
    </span>
  
</figure>

<p id="jIAhry">Duke (Depp), a magazine writer, is sent to cover a motorcycle race in Las Vegas and does an absolutely inadvisable variety and quantity of drugs. </p>
<p id="vmHBDF"><strong>Does the character get their story? </strong>Duke does finally write up his adventures, and it is implied that the narration during the movie is excerpted from the story he files. It’s definitely not what he was assigned, though, so <strong>5/10</strong>. </p>
<p id="hVk0Xn"><strong>Are they competent? </strong>Considering he spends almost every waking moment drifting in and out of a hallucinatory, ranting state, no. <strong>0/10 </strong></p>
<p id="uGKQDZ"><strong>Are they ethical?</strong> Duke doesn’t appear to fabricate anything in his stories, but the gleeful and terrifying crime spree he goes on while ostensibly reporting gets him a <strong>minus-5/10</strong>.<strong> </strong></p>
<p id="zpZcgq"><strong>How believable is the journalist? </strong>Duke would be impossible to believe, except that he was Hunter S. Thompson’s alter ego, and this is a dramatization of a thinly veiled memoir, so: <strong>5.5/10</strong> </p>
<p id="M6sd4T"><strong>Total: 5.5/10 </strong></p>
<h4 id="pbaSYw">33. Katie Holmes as Heather Holloway in <em>Thank You for Smoking</em> (2005)</h4>
<p id="gcpq31">Holloway is a doe-eyed reporter for the fictional <em>Washington Probe</em>, working on a profile of tobacco lobbyist Nick Naylor (Aaron Eckhart) whilst sleeping with him. </p>
<p id="0hSWaQ"><strong>Does the character get their story? </strong>She gets the juicy front-page profile she sets out to write. <strong>10/10 </strong></p>
<p id="KRtOha"><strong>Are they competent? </strong>Holloway is a great interviewer, but her primary reporting strategy appears to be seducing sources.<strong> 5/10</strong> </p>
<p id="aKPpQ6"><strong>Are they ethical?</strong> Absolutely not; she immediately sleeps with the subject of her piece. <strong>minus-5/10</strong></p>
<p id="5oZqbh"><strong>How believable is the journalist? </strong>Female journalists don’t sleep with their profile subjects! <strong>0/10 </strong></p>
<p id="ETy6yI"><strong>Total: 10/40 </strong></p>
<h4 id="z6xijh">32. Marcello Mastroianni as Marcello Rubini in <em>La Dolce Vita</em> (1960) </h4>
<p id="wCCTu0">Gossip columnist Rubini spends his days and nights doing plenty to gossip<em> about</em> but not much actual writing. As a character, Rubini is iconic. As a fictional journalist, he’s remarkably bad at his job. </p>
<p id="kv1kf9"><strong>Does the character get their story? </strong>At one point, Rubini tells a friend he is “gathering material,” and at another he is working on a novel, but he is never shown publishing much of anything. <strong>2/10 </strong></p>
<p id="q0ByEK"><strong>Are they competent? </strong>Rubini is not the most focused journalist, taking phone calls during a press junket and spending most of his time on various misadventures, so … no, not really.<strong> 3/10 </strong></p>
<p id="7OwWrH"><strong>Are they ethical?</strong> He pays his sources and (at least) attempts to sleep with a subject. (It’s ambiguous whether he succeeds.) <strong>4/10 </strong></p>
