1221px) 846px, (min-width: 880px) calc(100vw - 334px), 100vw" type="image/webp">


<img srcset="https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/JB-fk6MyxsgLx1ivJH2AFkCHxcw=/0x0:1500x999/320x0/filters:focal(0x0:1500x999):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/19394340/renner_kill_messenger.jpg 320w, https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/QELVC8bes3e4PIww5hq25vbCdQQ=/0x0:1500x999/520x0/filters:focal(0x0:1500x999):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/19394340/renner_kill_messenger.jpg 520w, https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/1UzMJZDmfq1Gc8CUacAhDTdFasA=/0x0:1500x999/720x0/filters:focal(0x0:1500x999):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/19394340/renner_kill_messenger.jpg 720w, https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/-C1jICamb69KBvi2NfV9BundOIk=/0x0:1500x999/920x0/filters:focal(0x0:1500x999):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/19394340/renner_kill_messenger.jpg 920w, https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/LE4DjmVOO9Pg-wpIMUG8bu_wWX8=/0x0:1500x999/1120x0/filters:focal(0x0:1500x999):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/19394340/renner_kill_messenger.jpg 1120w, https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/U6HGl8Q9Rsvh_kum_f89uIo2ekU=/0x0:1500x999/1320x0/filters:focal(0x0:1500x999):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/19394340/renner_kill_messenger.jpg 1320w, https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/05b0pJDsCWRwbx0J-JAjHLImPE4=/0x0:1500x999/1520x0/filters:focal(0x0:1500x999):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/19394340/renner_kill_messenger.jpg 1520w, https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/UJkJi5W-8ZAqa4x9HCa0Th0L2ko=/0x0:1500x999/1720x0/filters:focal(0x0:1500x999):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/19394340/renner_kill_messenger.jpg 1720w, https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/foUBlqMdwn3qNVNk4wxClUUUPUI=/0x0:1500x999/1920x0/filters:focal(0x0:1500x999):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/19394340/renner_kill_messenger.jpg 1920w" sizes="(min-width: 1221px) 846px, (min-width: 880px) calc(100vw - 334px), 100vw" alt="" data-upload-width="1500" src="https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/aASm69yFt0jBEGNUan1daj8rDCg=/0x0:1500x999/1200x0/filters:focal(0x0:1500x999):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/19394340/renner_kill_messenger.jpg">

</source></picture>

      
    </span>
    
  </span>
  
    <span class="e-image__meta">
      
      
        <cite>Focus Features</cite>
      
    </span>
  
</figure>

<p id="n1cw7E"><em>Kill the Messenger </em>is a dramatization of the fall of investigative journalist Gary Webb, whose “Dark Alliance” series for<em> The San Jose Mercury News </em>linked the crack cocaine trade in the United States with the CIA-backed Contra group in Nicaragua.</p>
<p id="Dyznl1"><strong>Does the character get their story? </strong>Yes—at first, and partially, and to his ultimate ruin. Webb publishes “Dark Alliance” to immediate acclaim, but he is not able to continue the series once other journalists begin to reinvestigate his story, poking holes and accusing Webb of flawed or outright wrong reporting. <strong>4/10 </strong></p>
<p id="4FZObt"><strong>Are they competent?</strong> Webb is shown to be especially adept at getting tricky sources to speak with him, and he was part of a Pulitzer Prize–winning team covering an earthquake earlier in his career, before the “Dark Alliance” story. He does, however, rely on a single unreliable source to tell him when court dates are, and shows up late.<strong> 7/10</strong> </p>
<p id="jfxlC7"><strong>Are they ethical?</strong> In real life, Webb’s journalism was the subject of intense debate, and many major news organizations poured resources into debunking his sourcing and the way his story was presented. <em>Kill the Messenger</em> takes Webb’s side, suggesting that his treatment at the hands of the media unfairly destroyed his career. While there are many legitimate critiques of the way the “Dark Alliance” series was presented and written, Webb was scrupulous and diligent in its reporting. <strong>8/10 </strong></p>
<p id="odFzOd"><strong>How believable is the journalist? </strong>Renner realistically schlumps himself up to play Webb. A little mustache goes a long way (although Renner remained slightly too jacked). <strong>7.5/10</strong></p>
<p id="ZEVXrb"><strong>Total: 26.5/40 </strong></p>
<h4 id="asUKMi">17. Holly Hunter as Jane Craig, William Hurt as Tom Grunick, and Albert Brooks as Aaron Altman in <em>Broadcast News</em> (1987)</h4>
<p id="bR0bXe">The love triangle at the center of <em>Broadcast News</em> is successful producer Jane, vapid but charming anchor Tom, and talented but sweaty reporter Aaron, who all work at the same network. It’s hard to consider them separately, so I’m taking them as an aggregate. </p>
<p id="22mA7e"><strong>Does the character get their story? </strong>Tom gets his big story about sexual harassment—but he conducts the interview in a manipulative way—while Aaron resigns, so we’ll give this an even <strong>5/10</strong>. </p>
<p id="vFXvRB"><strong>Are they competent? </strong>Jane’s at least a 9/10, but Albert and Tom are 5s at best, so we’ll give the group a <strong>6/10</strong>.</p>
<p id="NEMNor"><strong>Are they ethical?</strong> Jane and Albert are both fiercely idealistic and would rather die than compromise their journalistic ethics, while Tom is happy to stage his own tears to appear more sympathetic. We’ll do a <strong>6/10</strong> for the group. </p>
<p id="TFo2OD"><strong>How believable is the journalist? </strong><em>Broadcast News</em> is one of the most realistic movies about journalism on this list, from the horrible outfits to the layoffs to the adrenaline rushes when stories go well. <strong>10/10</strong></p>
<p id="fKGVfp"><strong>Total: 27/40 </strong></p>
<h4 id="M7YfP1">16. Julia Stiles as Elizabeth in <em>Hustlers </em>(2019) </h4>
  <figure class="e-image">
  <span class="e-image__inner">
    
    <span class="e-image__image " data-original="https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/19394343/julia_stiles_hustlers.jpg">
      
