  <source srcset="https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/3xBLD2EenHbwtkgJRLAmihFo3MA=/0x0:2048x1399/320x0/filters:focal(0x0:2048x1399):format(webp):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/19394355/presidents_men.jpg 320w, https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/M_ZBg6m05PZ7wH93x_gb1j1C8qA=/0x0:2048x1399/520x0/filters:focal(0x0:2048x1399):format(webp):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/19394355/presidents_men.jpg 520w, https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/J-caKkKoB-UnRDMGy8n0wvagNwQ=/0x0:2048x1399/720x0/filters:focal(0x0:2048x1399):format(webp):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/19394355/presidents_men.jpg 720w, https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/judKdogghblh7VQSWpG-Gzu4tOw=/0x0:2048x1399/920x0/filters:focal(0x0:2048x1399):format(webp):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/19394355/presidents_men.jpg 920w, https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/edXaVrJ-FUsRu_rlwxGzMgawqv8=/0x0:2048x1399/1120x0/filters:focal(0x0:2048x1399):format(webp):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/19394355/presidents_men.jpg 1120w, https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/hzM6fnjuU6RXR0VOrWEyG-EmCbI=/0x0:2048x1399/1320x0/filters:focal(0x0:2048x1399):format(webp):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/19394355/presidents_men.jpg 1320w, https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/k4UXHG4bKzZYvF1riAzjd17P2Vk=/0x0:2048x1399/1520x0/filters:focal(0x0:2048x1399):format(webp):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/19394355/presidents_men.jpg 1520w, https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/DUu3e5MxdYOKS9gdSKCo50z6X4M=/0x0:2048x1399/1720x0/filters:focal(0x0:2048x1399):format(webp):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/19394355/presidents_men.jpg 1720w, https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/2DdLJ-HMaH81av9sy34CLJ05B3I=/0x0:2048x1399/1920x0/filters:focal(0x0:2048x1399):format(webp):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/19394355/presidents_men.jpg 1920w" sizes="(min-width: 1221px) 846px, (min-width: 880px) calc(100vw - 334px), 100vw" type="image/webp">


<img srcset="https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/Vfh6C78J6yfodUT3se2C_Xda0gA=/0x0:2048x1399/320x0/filters:focal(0x0:2048x1399):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/19394355/presidents_men.jpg 320w, https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/rKYo6XiXhz7Nr2y9oXQ_D1D2TrU=/0x0:2048x1399/520x0/filters:focal(0x0:2048x1399):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/19394355/presidents_men.jpg 520w, https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/B9ctE8n8q1EE1B4nw-zd8e5nlFE=/0x0:2048x1399/720x0/filters:focal(0x0:2048x1399):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/19394355/presidents_men.jpg 720w, https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/c7xohyDNIlgprTv7hWEF-w_npA0=/0x0:2048x1399/920x0/filters:focal(0x0:2048x1399):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/19394355/presidents_men.jpg 920w, https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/MTW8XGMwhPhIk5fqc_hc8xs3fIE=/0x0:2048x1399/1120x0/filters:focal(0x0:2048x1399):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/19394355/presidents_men.jpg 1120w, https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/HTH8q0dTZJhCjcratVS1W7UWVJM=/0x0:2048x1399/1320x0/filters:focal(0x0:2048x1399):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/19394355/presidents_men.jpg 1320w, https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/YeLulN9XtvrUDg3jpWWbPYYMg0o=/0x0:2048x1399/1520x0/filters:focal(0x0:2048x1399):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/19394355/presidents_men.jpg 1520w, https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/MWn65MXrXj9XOEuwadDgEboB7ws=/0x0:2048x1399/1720x0/filters:focal(0x0:2048x1399):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/19394355/presidents_men.jpg 1720w, https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/6xjm0uDpYjBqu-6siO8eWWSj-fc=/0x0:2048x1399/1920x0/filters:focal(0x0:2048x1399):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/19394355/presidents_men.jpg 1920w" sizes="(min-width: 1221px) 846px, (min-width: 880px) calc(100vw - 334px), 100vw" alt="" data-upload-width="2048" src="https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/s32ipOGzwH1qypyBsurMmDPVCSs=/0x0:2048x1399/1200x0/filters:focal(0x0:2048x1399):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/19394355/presidents_men.jpg">

</source></picture>

      
    </span>
    
  </span>
  
    <span class="e-image__meta">
      
      
        <cite>Warner Bros.</cite>
      
    </span>
  
</figure>

<p id="2fqd0N">Two <em>Washington Post</em> reporters bring down a presidency. A classic for a reason. </p>
<p id="0HBnE3"><strong>Does the character get their story? </strong>Yes, they break the Watergate scandal and spur Nixon’s resignation. This is the most iconic story-getting of all time. <strong>50/10 </strong></p>
<p id="EmNpkB"><strong>Are they competent? </strong>Breaking this story is shown as a significant leap forward for the reporters, but then again, it’d be a significant leap forward for any journalist.<strong> 10/10</strong> </p>
<p id="kp0V99"><strong>Are they ethical?</strong> Yes. Although in real life the methods Woodward and Bernstein used might raise eyebrows today, in the film they are very upstanding. <strong>10/10 </strong></p>
<p id="24icW8"><strong>How believable is the journalist? </strong>Robert Redford and Dustin Hoffman are objectively too hot to be journalists in this movie, but their performances otherwise hew to real-life events, so:<strong> 8/10 </strong></p>
<p id="CxnK9v"><strong>Total: 78/40 </strong></p>
<h4 id="3ywNmm">1. Dr. Haing S. Ngor as Dith Pran and Sam Waterston as Sydney Schanberg in <em>The Killing Fields </em>(1984)</h4>
<p id="PYZz5T">Bringing up the front of the pack is another true-life journalism-hero story, but this one stands out because it has an extraordinary additional layer. It’s the story of real-life foreign correspondent Schanberg and his translator and freelance photographer Pran. <em>The Killing Fields </em>traces their two very different routes out of Cambodia during the Khmer Rouge’s genocide. </p>
<p id="t87ely"><strong>Does the character get their story? </strong>Their journalism within Cambodia during the film is interrupted by <a href="http://content.time.com/time/world/article/0,8599,1879785,00.html">Year Zero</a>, but they are reunited at the film’s end, with the suggestion that they’ll work together again. (And in real life, they did.) So:<strong> 7/10 </strong></p>
<p id="VdlkcO"><strong>Are they competent? </strong>They are both extremely resourceful and skilled, working together to send wartime dispatches until Schanberg evacuates and Pran flees. <strong>10/10 </strong></p>
<p id="TBGe2L"><strong>Are they ethical?</strong> Yes, they behave as ethically as they can throughout the film, although survival is certainly a far more important concern. <strong>10/10 </strong></p>
<p id="qKLwRn"><strong>How believable is the journalist? </strong>This is where this movie gets the highest marks. Waterston is great as Schanberg, but Ngor is incredible as Pran, partly because the actor also survived the Khmer Rouge and had to escape the labor camps to Thailand, so he had real-life experience to draw on. Ngor, who was a practicing gynecologist before Year Zero, lost his wife during childbirth while in the camps but managed to survive by eating bugs and crawling across the border into a refugee camp. Then he <a href="https://www.rogerebert.com/interviews/the-day-haing-s-ngor-won-the-oscar">was discovered</a> during casting for this film, and even though he had no acting experience he crushed it! Ngor won the Best Supporting Actor Oscar for this role—the second Asian actor to win an Oscar—and went on to work regularly in Hollywood. He kept working regularly for the next decade, but then he was murdered outside his home in Los Angeles in 1996. Three teenagers associated with a gang were arrested, although many people <a href="https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-2010-jan-21-la-me-ngor-murder21-2010jan21-story.html">suspect that he was assassinated</a> for drawing attention to the Khmer Rouge regime’s crimes against humanity. His life was absolutely tragic, and his performance as Dith Pran should be way more recognized than it is. <strong>1,000/10 </strong>for Dr. Haing S. Ngor! </p>
<p class="c-end-para" id="oZoyT3"><strong>Total: 1,027/40</strong></p>
</div>


